# === finding-df936616-0d70-48bf-ba31-e51a25efb307 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:finding-df936616-0d70-48bf-ba31-e51a25efb307> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-27T17:07:59.009969Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research ad tech sector impact\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "91ea36f6-9248-4f8f-a35c-65603e275bb8" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "semantic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-27T17:07:59.009719+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "Research complete. Here are the key findings:\n\n---\n\n## Q4 2025 Ad Tech Sector: Research Summary\n\n### Revenue Figures\n\n| Platform | Q4 Revenue | YoY Growth | vs. Estimates |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Google Search | $63.07B | +17% | Beat |\n| Google Total Ads | $82.28B | +13.5% | In-line |\n| YouTube | $11.38B | +8.7% | **Miss** (-$460M) |\n| Amazon Ads | $21.3B | **+23%** | Beat |\n| Meta (total) | $59.9B | +24% | Beat |\n| The Trade Desk | $847M | +14% | Slight beat; Q1 guide missed |\n| Snap (ads) | $1.48B | +5% | In-line |\n| Roku (platform) | $1.224B | +18% | Beat |\n| Pinterest | — | Soft | Miss + weak guide |\n\n### Key Findings\n\n**1. Google Search:** Accelerated all year (10% Q1 → 17% Q4). AI Overviews now in 50% of results, monetizing at parity with traditional ads. Market share rebounded in Q4 after 9 months of AI-driven erosion.\n\n**2. YouTube:** Record quarter ($11.38B) but missed estimates by $460M — notable because YouTube beat all year. Now larger than Disney+NBC+Paramount+WBD combined in ad revenue. Strong CTV position (12.7% of U.S. TV viewing).\n\n**3. Amazon:** Fastest-growing major platform at +23%. FY2025 ad revenue $68.6B. Prime Video ads now reach 315M viewers across 16 countries. Clearly #3 global digital ad platform.\n\n**4. Apple/ATT:** Structural damage from ATT is permanent — 55% decline in tracking rates, iOS UA costs still 20–30% elevated. Apple Search Ads now commands 35% of iOS app install spend (up from 25% at ATT launch). Google's April 2025 cookie pivot (consent prompt vs. forced deprecation) expected to replicate ATT's effect across the web.\n\n**5. Ad Tech Stocks:** Meta was the clear winner (+24%). The Trade Desk dropped -14.67% after-hours on weak Q1 guidance despite a Q4 beat — growth decelerated from ~27% to 14%, with CPG and automotive weakness. Pinterest missed. Roku swung to profitability validating CTV health.\n\n**6. AI in Advertising:** Meta is the most aggressive — quantified AI lifts on every surface (+3.5% FB clicks, +12% ad quality, +24% incremental conversions). Video AI tools hit $10B ARR. Targeting fully automated campaigns by 2026. Google's genAI product revenue grew ~400% YoY.\n\n**7. Q4 Seasonality:** First \"quarter trillion dollar\" holiday season — $257.8B in online spending (+6.8% YoY). U.S. digital ad spend exceeded $40B in Q4 (+13% YoY). Earlier holiday shopping trend (more Sept/Oct spending) shifted when ad dollars ramped.\n\n**8. Privacy:** Google abandoned forced cookie deprecation (consent prompt instead). Contextual targeting now within 5–8% of cookie-based performance. Clean rooms booming. 20+ U.S. states have privacy laws; EU enforcing Consent Mode v2. First-party data walled gardens (Google, Meta, Amazon, Apple) are structurally advantaged.\n\n### Bottom Line\nThe Q4 2025 holiday quarter was broadly strong for digital advertising. **Amazon and Meta were the clear outperformers**. Google Search is healthy, but YouTube's miss and The Trade Desk's growth deceleration signal the competitive landscape is intensifying for non-AI-native platforms. AI investment is now the primary differentiator separating winners from laggards." ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "0.8"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "611b8911-27d2-43c3-99dd-0cf8ea88bd9c" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Research complete. Here are the key findings:\n\n---\n\n## Q4 2025 Ad Tech Sector: Research Summary\n\n### Revenue Figures\n\n| Platform | Q4 Revenue | YoY Growth | vs. Estimates |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Google Search | $63.07B | +17% | Beat |\n| Google Total Ads | $82.28B | +13.5% | In-line |\n| YouTube | $11.38B | +8.7% | **Miss** (-$460M) |\n| Amazon Ads | $21.3B | **+23%** | Beat |\n| Meta (total) | $59.9B | +24% | Beat |\n| The Trade Desk | $847M | +14% | Slight beat; Q1 guide missed |\n| Snap (ads) | $1.48B | +5% | In-line |\n| Roku (platform) | $1.224B | +18% | Beat |\n| Pinterest | — | Soft | Miss + weak guide |\n\n### Key Findings\n\n**1. Google Search:** Accelerated all year (10% Q1 → 17% Q4). AI Overviews now in 50% of results, monetizing at parity with traditional ads. Market share rebounded in Q4 after 9 months of AI-driven erosion.\n\n**2. YouTube:** Record quarter ($11.38B) but missed estimates by $460M — notable because YouTube beat all year. Now larger than Disney+NBC+Paramount+WBD combined in ad revenue. Strong CTV position (12.7% of U.S. TV viewing).\n\n**3. Amazon:** Fastest-growing major platform at +23%. FY2025 ad revenue $68.6B. Prime Video ads now reach 315M viewers across 16 countries. Clearly #3 global digital ad platform.\n\n**4. Apple/ATT:** Structural damage from ATT is permanent — 55% decline in tracking rates, iOS UA costs still 20–30% elevated. Apple Search Ads now commands 35% of iOS app install spend (up from 25% at ATT launch). Google's April 2025 cookie pivot (consent prompt vs. forced deprecation) expected to replicate ATT's effect across the web.\n\n**5. Ad Tech Stocks:** Meta was the clear winner (+24%). The Trade Desk dropped -14.67% after-hours on weak Q1 guidance despite a Q4 beat — growth decelerated from ~27% to 14%, with CPG and automotive weakness. Pinterest missed. Roku swung to profitability validating CTV health.\n\n**6. AI in Advertising:** Meta is the most aggressive — quantified AI lifts on every surface (+3.5% FB clicks, +12% ad quality, +24% incremental conversions). Video AI tools hit $10B ARR. Targeting fully automated campaigns by 2026. Google's genAI product revenue grew ~400% YoY.\n\n**7. Q4 Seasonality:** First \"quarter trillion dollar\" holiday season — $257.8B in online spending (+6.8% YoY). U.S. digital ad spend exceeded $40B in Q4 (+13% YoY). Earlier holiday shopping trend (more Sept/Oct spending) shifted when ad dollars ramped.\n\n**8. Privacy:** Google abandoned forced cookie deprecation (consent prompt instead). Contextual targeting now within 5–8% of cookie-based performance. Clean rooms booming. 20+ U.S. states have privacy laws; EU enforcing Consent Mode v2. First-party data walled gardens (Google, Meta, Amazon, Apple) are structurally advantaged.\n\n### Bottom Line\nThe Q4 2025 holiday quarter was broadly strong for digital advertising. **Amazon and Meta were the clear outperformers**. Google Search is healthy, but YouTube's miss and The Trade Desk's growth deceleration signal the competitive landscape is intensifying for non-AI-native platforms. AI investment is now the primary differentiator separating winners from laggards." ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Research complete. Here are the key findings:\n\n---\n\n## Q4 2025 Ad Tech Sector: Research Summary\n\n###" ;
	a <https://schema.org/SemanticMemory> .


# === finding-e34f9275-f9af-4992-a206-b42ed5551349 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:finding-e34f9275-f9af-4992-a206-b42ed5551349> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-27T17:32:38.576813Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Write executive summary README\",\"coder\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "91ea36f6-9248-4f8f-a35c-65603e275bb8" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "semantic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-27T17:32:38.576624+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "The write needs permission approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-parallel-stocks/analysis/README.md` so the executive summary can be saved.\n\nThe file I've prepared is a cohesive ~1,400-word executive summary that:\n\n1. **Opens with a thesis** — \"every company beat; every company that disclosed outsized capex sold off\" — and traces that contradiction through the entire cycle\n2. **Earnings at a glance table** — all 4 companies with revenue, YoY, beat magnitude, and stock reaction in one view\n3. **The capex shock section** — the full $620–640B commitment table with shock magnitudes; explains why Microsoft absorbed its guide while Amazon and Alphabet sold off (telegraphing vs. surprise)\n4. **Company highlights** — tight 5–6 bullet summaries for each company with links to full reports\n5. **Sector roundup** — cloud (backlog convergence), ad-tech (AI Overviews vindicated, walled-garden consolidation complete), semiconductors (SOX +52%, TSMC as single chokepoint, HBM supercycle, Broadcom's $100B+ roadmap)\n6. **Cross-cutting insights** — the 5 non-obvious patterns from correlations.md: capex shock as new market signal, the Anthropic axis, opacity of AI revenue, Apple's asymmetric position, and the 2027–2028 depreciation cliff\n7. **Forward-looking table** — 7 watch items with timeframes\n8. **Report index** — navigation links to all 8 underlying files" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "0.8"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "4d466789-fa10-4958-9533-b7063cc08d76" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "The write needs permission approval. Please approve the write to `/private/tmp/swarm-parallel-stocks/analysis/README.md` so the executive summary can be saved.\n\nThe file I've prepared is a cohesive ~1,400-word executive summary that:\n\n1. **Opens with a thesis** — \"every company beat; every company that disclosed outsized capex sold off\" — and traces that contradiction through the entire cycle\n2. **Earnings at a glance table** — all 4 companies with revenue, YoY, beat magnitude, and stock reaction in one view\n3. **The capex shock section** — the full $620–640B commitment table with shock magnitudes; explains why Microsoft absorbed its guide while Amazon and Alphabet sold off (telegraphing vs. surprise)\n4. **Company highlights** — tight 5–6 bullet summaries for each company with links to full reports\n5. **Sector roundup** — cloud (backlog convergence), ad-tech (AI Overviews vindicated, walled-garden consolidation complete), semiconductors (SOX +52%, TSMC as single chokepoint, HBM supercycle, Broadcom's $100B+ roadmap)\n6. **Cross-cutting insights** — the 5 non-obvious patterns from correlations.md: capex shock as new market signal, the Anthropic axis, opacity of AI revenue, Apple's asymmetric position, and the 2027–2028 depreciation cliff\n7. **Forward-looking table** — 7 watch items with timeframes\n8. **Report index** — navigation links to all 8 underlying files" ;
