# === memory-426fbc9e-d537-4c61-9dc4-219ead841301 ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-426fbc9e-d537-4c61-9dc4-219ead841301> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-27T17:05:37.762833Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/topics> "[\"Research semiconductor sector impact\",\"Search semiconductor sector reactions\",\"researcher\"]" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/tool_name> "researcher" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/structured_data> "null" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/run_id> "91ea36f6-9248-4f8f-a35c-65603e275bb8" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/memory_type> "episodic" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/created_at> "2026-03-27T17:05:37.762312+00:00" ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/content> "Here is a structured summary of all findings on semiconductor sector reactions to Q4 2025 big tech earnings:\n\n---\n\n## Semiconductor Sector: Q4 2025 Big Tech Earnings Impact\n\n### 1. AI Chip Demand & Capex Signals\n\nBig tech collectively announced ~**$650-700B in 2026 AI capex** (nearly double 2025's ~$380B):\n- Amazon: $200B (+56%), Alphabet: $175-185B (+98%), Meta: $115-135B (+74%), Microsoft: $120B+\n- All hyperscalers reported demand is **supply-constrained**, not demand-constrained\n\n**NVIDIA's paradox**: Despite record Q4 FY2026 revenue of **$68.1B (+73% YoY)**, the stock *dropped 5.46%* ($260B market cap erased). When each hyperscaler announced massive capex increases, NVIDIA stock barely moved — classic \"buy the rumor, sell the news.\"\n\n### 2. TSMC & Supply Chain\n\nTSMC Q4 FY2025: Revenue +20.5% YoY, net income +35%. HPC = **55% of revenue**, smartphones = 32%. N2 (2nm) entered high-volume manufacturing in Q4 2025. 2026 capex guidance: **$52-56B** (70-80% to advanced nodes), Q1 2026 revenue guidance +38% YoY. Qualcomm shifted premium orders back to TSMC after Samsung yield problems.\n\n### 3. SOX Index\n\n- SOX hit **8,498 on Feb 25, 2026** — fresh highs during earnings season\n- **12-month return: +52%**\n- Best performer: **Micron (MU) +281%** — memory supercycle winner\n- Worst: **Qualcomm (QCOM) -17.7%** — lost relevance in AI infrastructure narrative\n\n### 4. Custom Silicon Trends\n\n| Company | Chip | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| Google | TPU Ironwood (7th gen) | Released Nov 2025; **58% custom cloud AI market share** |\n| Amazon | Trainium3 (3nm) | In production; $10B+ annual run-rate for AWS custom silicon |\n| Microsoft | Maia 200 | Deployed Jan 2026; claims 3x FP4 perf vs. Trainium3 |\n| NVIDIA | B300 Blackwell Ultra | Still performance leader; CUDA moat holds for training |\n\nCustom ASIC shipments projected **+44.6% in 2026** vs. GPU at **+16.1%** — structural shift underway, but CUDA ecosystem keeps NVIDIA dominant in frontier model training.\n\n### 5. Memory (Micron, SK Hynix, Samsung)\n\nHBM is sold out. Literally. Both SK Hynix and Micron reported capacity \"essentially sold out\" through 2026. Key data:\n- 2026 HBM market: **$54.6B** (+58% YoY per BofA); TrendForce sees +70% YoY\n- Micron FQ1 2026: $13.64B revenue (+57%), gross margins >50%\n- SK Hynix holds **>50% HBM market share**; BofA calls 2026 a \"supercycle like the 1990s\"\n- HBM3E = ~2/3 of 2026 shipments; HBM4 ramping\n\n### 6. Broadcom & Marvell — Custom Silicon Beneficiaries\n\n**Broadcom** is the biggest indirect winner:\n- AI revenue Q1 FY2026: **$8.4B (+106% YoY)** = 43% of total revenue\n- Q2 FY2026 guidance: **$10.7B AI revenue** (+140% YoY)\n- CEO Hock Tan: clear line of sight to **>$100B AI chip revenue** by late 2027/early 2028\n- 70-80% share of custom XPU market; $73B backlog; TSMC 3nm/2nm capacity locked through decade-end\n\n**Marvell**: Data center revenue +39% YoY, but positioned as \"niche leader\" vs. Broadcom.\n\n### Key Analyst Takeaways\n\n1. AI capex announcements validated the entire semiconductor supply chain — but NVIDIA's premium valuation made even record numbers a \"sell the news\" event\n2. Memory is the sleeper winner: Micron led the SOX index, HBM shortage driving margin expansion across the board\n3. Broadcom + Marvell benefit more from the custom silicon shift than NVIDIA loses from it — hyperscalers buy both\n4. TSMC = the one foundry everyone needs — insulated from GPU vs. custom ASIC debate since it makes both\n\nAll findings saved to `semiconductor_q4_2025_research.md` in memory." ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/confidence> "1"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#double> ;
	<http://tesserai.io/ontology/agent_id> "9b537b6e-1ee5-43d0-8f73-a2c330f137d8" ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Here is a structured summary of all findings on semiconductor sector reactions to Q4 2025 big tech earnings:\n\n---\n\n## Semiconductor Sector: Q4 2025 Big Tech Earnings Impact\n\n### 1. AI Chip Demand & Capex Signals\n\nBig tech collectively announced ~**$650-700B in 2026 AI capex** (nearly double 2025's ~$380B):\n- Amazon: $200B (+56%), Alphabet: $175-185B (+98%), Meta: $115-135B (+74%), Microsoft: $120B+\n- All hyperscalers reported demand is **supply-constrained**, not demand-constrained\n\n**NVIDIA's paradox**: Despite record Q4 FY2026 revenue of **$68.1B (+73% YoY)**, the stock *dropped 5.46%* ($260B market cap erased). When each hyperscaler announced massive capex increases, NVIDIA stock barely moved — classic \"buy the rumor, sell the news.\"\n\n### 2. TSMC & Supply Chain\n\nTSMC Q4 FY2025: Revenue +20.5% YoY, net income +35%. HPC = **55% of revenue**, smartphones = 32%. N2 (2nm) entered high-volume manufacturing in Q4 2025. 2026 capex guidance: **$52-56B** (70-80% to advanced nodes), Q1 2026 revenue guidance +38% YoY. Qualcomm shifted premium orders back to TSMC after Samsung yield problems.\n\n### 3. SOX Index\n\n- SOX hit **8,498 on Feb 25, 2026** — fresh highs during earnings season\n- **12-month return: +52%**\n- Best performer: **Micron (MU) +281%** — memory supercycle winner\n- Worst: **Qualcomm (QCOM) -17.7%** — lost relevance in AI infrastructure narrative\n\n### 4. Custom Silicon Trends\n\n| Company | Chip | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| Google | TPU Ironwood (7th gen) | Released Nov 2025; **58% custom cloud AI market share** |\n| Amazon | Trainium3 (3nm) | In production; $10B+ annual run-rate for AWS custom silicon |\n| Microsoft | Maia 200 | Deployed Jan 2026; claims 3x FP4 perf vs. Trainium3 |\n| NVIDIA | B300 Blackwell Ultra | Still performance leader; CUDA moat holds for training |\n\nCustom ASIC shipments projected **+44.6% in 2026** vs. GPU at **+16.1%** — structural shift underway, but CUDA ecosystem keeps NVIDIA dominant in frontier model training.\n\n### 5. Memory (Micron, SK Hynix, Samsung)\n\nHBM is sold out. Literally. Both SK Hynix and Micron reported capacity \"essentially sold out\" through 2026. Key data:\n- 2026 HBM market: **$54.6B** (+58% YoY per BofA); TrendForce sees +70% YoY\n- Micron FQ1 2026: $13.64B revenue (+57%), gross margins >50%\n- SK Hynix holds **>50% HBM market share**; BofA calls 2026 a \"supercycle like the 1990s\"\n- HBM3E = ~2/3 of 2026 shipments; HBM4 ramping\n\n### 6. Broadcom & Marvell — Custom Silicon Beneficiaries\n\n**Broadcom** is the biggest indirect winner:\n- AI revenue Q1 FY2026: **$8.4B (+106% YoY)** = 43% of total revenue\n- Q2 FY2026 guidance: **$10.7B AI revenue** (+140% YoY)\n- CEO Hock Tan: clear line of sight to **>$100B AI chip revenue** by late 2027/early 2028\n- 70-80% share of custom XPU market; $73B backlog; TSMC 3nm/2nm capacity locked through decade-end\n\n**Marvell**: Data center revenue +39% YoY, but positioned as \"niche leader\" vs. Broadcom.\n\n### Key Analyst Takeaways\n\n1. AI capex announcements validated the entire semiconductor supply chain — but NVIDIA's premium valuation made even record numbers a \"sell the news\" event\n2. Memory is the sleeper winner: Micron led the SOX index, HBM shortage driving margin expansion across the board\n3. Broadcom + Marvell benefit more from the custom silicon shift than NVIDIA loses from it — hyperscalers buy both\n4. TSMC = the one foundry everyone needs — insulated from GPU vs. custom ASIC debate since it makes both\n\nAll findings saved to `semiconductor_q4_2025_research.md` in memory." ;
	<http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "[researcher] Here is a structured summary of all findings on semiconductor sector reactions t" ;
	a <https://schema.org/EpisodicMemory> .


# === memory-4727dea3-d09d-42a6-a0ae-6c6d1f1a34cb ===
<urn:tesserai:twin:memory-4727dea3-d09d-42a6-a0ae-6c6d1f1a34cb> <http://tesserai.io/ontology/createdAt> "2026-03-27T17:07:11.915267Z"^^<http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#dateTime> ;
